                  "working": "$\\sqrt{x^{\\frac{4}{3}}} = (x^{\\frac{4}{3}})^{\\frac{1}{2}} = x^{\\frac{4}{3} \\times \\frac{1}{2}} = x^{\\frac{2}{3}}$",
                  "reasoning": "Power of a power rule: $(x^a)^b = x^{ab}$."
                }
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "partId": "b",
            "questionText": "Find an expression for b in terms of a and c. $\\frac{49^{2a}}{7^{b}}=343^{4c}$",
            "marks": 3,
            "answerType": "algebraic",
            "solution": {
              "finalAnswer": "$b = 4a - 12c$",
              "stepByStep": [
                {
                  "step": 1,
                  "explanation": "Convert all terms to the same base (base 7).",
                  "working": "$49 = 7^2$, so $49^{2a} = (7^2)^{2a} = 7^{4a}$\n$343 = 7^3$, so $343^{4c} = (7^3)^{4c} = 7^{12c}$",
                  "reasoning": "Indices equations are easiest to solve when bases are identical."
                },
                {
                  "step": 2,
                  "explanation": "Substitute back into the equation and simplify LHS.",
                  "working": "$\\frac{7^{4a}}{7^b} = 7^{12c}$\n$7^{4a-b} = 7^{12c}$",
                  "reasoning": "Division law of indices: $x^m \\div x^n = x^{m-n}$."
                },
                {
                  "step": 3,
                  "explanation": "Equate the powers and solve for b.",
                  "working": "$4a - b = 12c$\n$b = 4a - 12c$",
                  "reasoning": "If bases are equal, the exponents must be equal."
                }
              ]
            }
          }
